      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/ncv",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Code verification via comparison to analytical solutions or published benchmarks for structural mechanics problems representative of pedicle screw loading. Required: at least one benchmark comparison with documented error; achieved: three independent benchmark comparisons (cantilever beam, Hertzian contact, elastoplastic cylinder) all within 1% of analytical solutions."
      },
      "rationale": "Three code verification benchmarks executed: (1) cantilever beam bending — FEA vs. Euler-Bernoulli analytical solution, max error 0.3%; (2) Hertzian contact stress — FEA vs. analytical, max error 0.8%; (3) elastoplastic thick-walled cylinder under internal pressure — FEA vs. Nadai analytical solution, max error 0.9%. All benchmarks documented in code verification report NCV-2023-012.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/evidence/code-verification-report-2023-012"
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/disc-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Systematic mesh convergence study using Richardson extrapolation; Grid Convergence Index (GCI) < 1% for all QoIs on the production mesh. Required: documented convergence study with GCI reported; achieved: three-level convergence study with GCI < 0.5% for all three QoIs."
      },
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh convergence study conducted on the non-cannulated screw construct model: coarse (185k elements), medium (412k elements), and fine (891k elements). Richardson extrapolation applied per Roache (1998). GCI values: stiffness 0.31%, yield force 0.44%, force at 40 mm 0.38%. Production mesh uses medium density (412k elements) as optimal balance of accuracy and computational cost. Mesh convergence report MCR-2023-008 documents all results.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/evidence/mesh-convergence-report-2023-008"
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/solver-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Iterative solver convergence criteria documented and verified; energy residual < 1e-6 and force residual < 1e-4 for all load steps. Time-stepping sensitivity study confirms load-step-independent results within 0.5%."
      },
      "rationale": "Nonlinear static analysis uses full Newton-Raphson iteration with line search. Convergence criteria: energy residual 1e-6, force residual 1e-4, displacement residual 1e-3 — all satisfied at each load increment. Load-step sensitivity study: 50-step vs. 100-step solutions differ by < 0.2% in all QoIs. Solver error contribution to total uncertainty budget estimated at < 0.3% via perturbation analysis. Results documented in solver verification log SVL-2023-003.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/evidence/solver-verification-log-2023-003"
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/use-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Documented modeling protocol with independent peer review; at least one independent analyst reproduces key QoI predictions within 1% using the same protocol and inputs. Required: documented protocol; achieved: documented protocol plus independent reproduction study."
      },
      "rationale": "FEA modeling protocol MP-2023-NC-001 specifies all modeling decisions: geometry import procedure, contact definitions (frictional, mu=0.2), boundary conditions, material assignments, and post-processing scripts. An independent analyst at FDA CDRH reproduced stiffness (155.9 N/mm, 0.2% difference), yield force (1241 N, 0.2% difference), and force at 40 mm (1387 N, 0.1% difference) using the same protocol. Protocol review completed by senior engineer with sign-off documented in USE-2023-review-log.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/evidence/use-error-review-2023"
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/model-form",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Model form assumptions documented and justified for the compression-bending regime: continuum isotropic elastoplastic constitutive model for Ti-6Al-4V, frictional contact at screw-rod and screw-block interfaces. Sensitivity of QoIs to model form choices (contact friction coefficient, plasticity hardening law) quantified and within 5% over plausible parameter ranges."
      },
      "rationale": "Continuum isotropic elastoplastic model (bilinear kinematic hardening) adopted for Ti-6Al-4V screw and rod components. UHMWPE block modeled as linear elastic with experimentally characterized modulus. Frictional contact (Coulomb, mu=0.2 ± 0.05) at all interfaces. Model form sensitivity study: varying friction coefficient from 0.15 to 0.25 changes stiffness by 1.8%, yield force by 2.1%, force at 40 mm by 2.4% — all within 5% acceptance band. Isotropic vs. anisotropic hardening comparison shows < 1.5% difference for the monotonic loading regime of F1717. Model form justification documented in MFJ-2023-007.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/evidence/model-form-justification-2023-007"
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/model-inputs",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "All material properties and geometric inputs sourced from traceable measurements or certified material test reports. Uncertainty distributions assigned to all inputs with non-negligible sensitivity. Required: traceable inputs with uncertainty bounds; achieved: traceable inputs with full probability distributions and global sensitivity analysis (Sobol indices) identifying dominant inputs."
      },
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V material properties (E=114 GPa ± 2 GPa, yield stress=880 MPa ± 15 MPa, tangent modulus=1.2 GPa ± 0.15 GPa) sourced from material certification reports for production lot MFG-2022-TI-047 and supplemented by in-house tensile coupon testing (N=6). UHMWPE block modulus (680 MPa ± 40 MPa) from supplier datasheet with in-house validation. Geometric dimensions from CMM measurements of 5 production screws (mean ± 2σ tolerances). Global Sobol sensitivity analysis identifies yield stress (Si=0.41) and screw root radius (Si=0.28) as dominant inputs. Full input uncertainty report IUR-2023-015 archived.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/evidence/input-uncertainty-report-2023-015"
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/test-samples",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Test specimens are production-representative components from the same manufacturing lot as the device under evaluation. N ≥ 10 specimens tested across ≥ 2 independent laboratories. Dimensional inspection confirms specimens are within drawing tolerances."
      },
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs assembled from production components (lot MFG-2022-TI-047). Six constructs tested at FDA CDRH biomechanics laboratory; five constructs tested at independent contract laboratory (Exponent, Inc.). All specimens inspected by CMM prior to testing; all dimensions within ±0.05 mm of nominal. Construct assembly followed DePuy Synthes IFU with torque-controlled screw seating (4 Nm). Sample traceability documented in test sample log TSL-2022-NC-011.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/evidence/test-sample-log-2022-nc-011"
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/test-conditions",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Test conditions replicate ASTM F1717 protocol with documented environmental controls. Multiple loading rates or conditions explored to characterize rate sensitivity. Required: full F1717 compliance with documented environmental conditions; achieved: full F1717 compliance but only single loading rate (5 mm/min) tested — rate sensitivity not directly characterized experimentally."
      },
      "rationale": "Testing conducted per ASTM F1717-21 at 5 mm/min displacement rate, 37°C phosphate-buffered saline bath, 6-degree offset angle. Environmental conditions logged throughout testing. Only a single loading rate tested due to resource constraints; rate sensitivity addressed analytically via viscoelastic sensitivity analysis of UHMWPE block (< 3% effect on peak force at rates 1-10 mm/min). This factor does not meet the required level of 3; risk accepted per COU decision record with documented rationale that the analytical rate sensitivity argument is conservative and the single-rate experimental result is sufficient for the intended regulatory submission.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/evidence/test-conditions-report-2022-nc-011"
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/equiv-inputs",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "FEA model inputs (material properties, geometry, boundary conditions, loading) are demonstrably equivalent to experimental test conditions. Systematic mapping of all model inputs to experimental measurements documented; any discrepancies quantified and incorporated into uncertainty budget."
      },
      "rationale": "Formal input equivalency matrix (IEM-2023-NC-001) maps each FEA input parameter to its experimental counterpart. Material property inputs sourced from same production lot as test specimens (MFG-2022-TI-047). FEA geometry derived from CMM measurements of test specimens. Boundary conditions replicate F1717 fixture geometry (rod span 44 mm, offset 6°) as measured post-test. Screw seating torque converted to initial contact pressure via Hertzian contact calibration. No unresolved discrepancies; all differences incorporated into UQ via Monte Carlo propagation.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/evidence/input-equivalency-matrix-2023-nc-001"
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/output-comparison",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Quantitative comparison of all three QoIs using both relative error (<10%) and normalized validation metric E/uval < 1.96. Comparison includes propagated simulation uncertainty and experimental measurement uncertainty. Required: quantitative comparison with uncertainty; achieved: full probabilistic comparison with E/uval metric, relative error, and additional force-displacement curve comparison."
      },
      "rationale": "All three QoIs satisfy both acceptance criteria: stiffness (relative error 1.6%, E/uval 0.41), yield force (relative error 2.2%, E/uval 0.54), force at 40 mm (relative error 2.3%, E/uval 0.52). Additionally, full force-displacement curves compared using area metric (Ferson et al.): metric value 0.08 (< 0.20 threshold). Two-laboratory experimental consistency verified: Levene's test for equal variances (p=0.34 for stiffness) and t-test for equal means (p=0.71 for stiffness) confirm no significant inter-laboratory effect. Comparison documented in validation comparison report VCR-2024-NC-001.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/evidence/validation-comparison-report-2024-nc-001"
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/qoi-relevance",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly linked to clinical failure modes and regulatory submission requirements. Traceability from QoIs to device performance specifications and FDA guidance documented."
      },
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness is directly related to postoperative spinal segment mobility and implant fatigue life. Yield force defines the onset of permanent deformation relevant to screw fracture risk. Force at 40 mm displacement characterizes post-yield energy absorption relevant to catastrophic failure. All three QoIs are required by ASTM F1717-21 and referenced in FDA guidance document 'Testing and Labeling Recommendations for Pedicle Screw Spinal Systems' (2021). QoI traceability matrix QTM-2023-001 maps each QoI to device performance specification DPS-NC-2022-003.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/evidence/qoi-traceability-matrix-2023-001"
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/va-relevance",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Validation activities (F1717 bench testing of non-cannulated 7.5 mm construct) are directly representative of the COU (FEA prediction of the same construct under the same loading). Scope of validation covers the full operating range of the device as defined in the COU. Any gaps between validation scope and COU scope are identified and their impact on credibility assessed."
      },
      "rationale": "The validation activity (ASTM F1717 static compression-bending, non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw, N=11, two laboratories) is directly representative of the COU: same device geometry, same loading mode, same test standard, same QoIs. The FEA model is applied to exactly the conditions tested — no extrapolation is required. The single gap identified (one loading rate, addressed under Test Conditions factor) is considered low-risk for the static compression-bending COU. Validation relevance assessment documented in VRA-2024-NC-001, reviewed and approved by credibility assessment team.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/evidence/validation-relevance-assessment-2024-nc-001"
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-accepted-2024",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/actor/credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team reviewed all 13 V&V 40 factors and determined that the FEA model ensemble has sufficient credibility for its intended use in the COU. Twelve of thirteen factors meet or exceed their required credibility levels. The single factor below required level (Test conditions, achieved 2 vs. required 3) is accepted on the basis of: (1) the analytical rate sensitivity argument demonstrating < 3% QoI variation over the physiologically relevant loading rate range; (2) the strong quantitative validation results for all three QoIs (all E/uval < 0.60, all relative errors < 3%); and (3) the direct one-to-one correspondence between validation activities and the COU scope, which minimizes extrapolation risk. The normalized validation metric E/uval < 1.96 is satisfied for all QoIs across both laboratories, and the force-displacement curve area metric (0.08) is well within the 0.20 threshold. The model risk level 3 (Medium) is consistent with the Medium model influence and Medium decision consequence of this Class II device COU. The decision to accept is supported by the complete provenance chain from foundational material characterization through mesh convergence, code verification, and experimental comparison, with full uncertainty quantification propagated through Monte Carlo analysis. No unresolved discrepancies or open action items remain.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z",
    "supportingEvidence": [
      "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/evidence/validation-comparison-report-2024-nc-001",
      "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/evidence/input-uncertainty-report-2023-015",
      "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/evidence/mesh-convergence-report-2023-008",
      "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/evidence/code-verification-report-2023-012",
      "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/evidence/sqa-report-2022-047"
    ]
  },
